o, Toscana, Itálie"},"da":{"about 1125–1195":"omkring 1125–1195","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1171–Male":"1171–Afdød","1130–Female":"1130–Afdød","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Afdød","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1125":"1125","about 1125":"omkring 1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","Comune di Santa Fiora, provincia di Grosseto, Toscana, Italia":"Santa Fiora, Grosseto, Toscana, Italien"},"nl":{"about 1125–1195":"circa 1125–1195","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1171–Male":"1171–Overleden","1130–Female":"1130–Overleden","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Overleden","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1125":"1125","about 1125":"circa 1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","Comune di Santa Fiora, provincia di Grosseto, Toscana, Italia":"Santa Fiora, Grosseto, Toscana, Italië"},"en":{"about 1125–1195":"about 1125–1195","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1171–Male":"1171–Deceased","1130–Female":"1130–Deceased","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1125":"1125","about 1125":"about 1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","Comune di Santa Fiora, provincia di Grosseto, Toscana, Italia":"Santa Fiora, Grosseto, Tuscany, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"e","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鄂, a short form of present-day Hubei province: (i) from E (鄂), the name of an ancient state (located in Henan province), destroyed by the king Zhou, last king of the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) from the placename E (鄂), the name of a fief (located in Shanxi province) in the state of Jin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the placename E (鄂), the name of a fief (located in Hubei province) granted to the royal members of the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) possibly a surname from minority ethnic groups in southwestern China. (v) said to be adopted as a new surname by Yue Ting, who changed his original name Yue (嶽) to E (鄂), because he fled to Huangmei in present-day Hubei province (called E (鄂) at that time) to avoid persecution after his father Yue Fei (1103–1142  AD ), a famous Chinese general in the Southern Song dynasty (1127 – 1279  AD ), was put to death by the then emperor."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sovana","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Alberto, Blanca, Eugenio, Francisco, Gustavo, Juan, Luis, Manuel, Alfonso, Carlos, Eduardo.","Spanish and Aragonese: habitational name from any of numerous places called (La) Solana, derived from <i>solano</i> ‘place exposed to the sun’ (see   Solano  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Solano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Juan, Francisco, Manuel, Carlos, Jorge, Pedro, Julio, Miguel, Fernando, Jaime.","Spanish and Aragonese: habitational name from any of the places called Solano (Burgos and Málaga provinces) or El Solano (Huesca, Aragon), named with <i>solano</i> ‘place exposed to the sun’ (from Late Latin <i>solanum</i>, a derivative of <i>sōl</i> ‘sun’).","Spanish and Portuguese: from a personal name adopted in honor of Saint Francisco Solano, a 17th-century missionary to South America."]}]},{"name":"VII","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ildebrandino VII Aldobrandeschi e Sovana Conte di Santa Fiora e Sovana was born about 1125, in Santa Fiora, Grosseto, Tuscany, Italy, his father, Ildebrandino Novello Aldobrandeschi, was 47 and his mother, Emilia della Gherardesca, was 37. He had at least 1 son with Maria Aldobrandeschi di Prato. He died in 1195, at the age of 71."},"et":{"about 1125–1195":"umbes 1125–1195","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1125":"1125","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","Comune di Santa Fiora, provincia di Grosseto, Toscana, Italia":"Santa Fiora, Grosseto, Toscana, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1125–1195":"noin 1125–1195","1110–1152":"1110–1152","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1171–Male":"1171–Kuollut","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1080–1171":"1080–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1125":"1125","about 1125":"noin 1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","C